Modeling the growth of non-decomposed municipal solid waste in US landfills¶

Introduction¶

In the United States, a large proportion of municipal solid waste (MSW) - commonly known as trash or garbage - is delivered to landfills where it is compacted and buried. In 2017, the percentage breakdown of the different destinations for MSW were 52% landfilled (127 million metric tons), 25% recycled, 13% combusted, and 10% composted [1]. The long duration of time that some MSW takes to decompose is an environmental concern as there is the potential for large swaths of future land to be occupied by landfills containing waste that has not yet decomposed.

We call this MSW the non-decomposed or remaining waste in landfills. While decomposed waste might be considered as having 'returned to the Earth', non-decomposed waste remains largely in its original, recognizable form. There is a pressing environmental need for an accurate model that describes the growth - and potential stabilization - in the amount of non-decomposed MSW in US landfills. Such a model might be extended to other nations, although this text focuses on the US due to the availability of high-quality data provided by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).

Model inputs¶

The ten primary types of MSW reported by the EPA are: food, plastic, paper, wood, textiles, steel, yard trimmings, glass, rubber and leather, and aluminum. Undescribed other types of MSW representing less than 5% of the total amount landfilled are not be considered. To create a basic model, a few inputs are needed:

  1. The amount of each MSW type landfilled, for both past and future years.
  2. The decomposition functions for each MSW type.
  3. Densities of each MSW type (to calculate the volume occupied by the non-decomposed MSW type).
  4. Median landfill depth (to calculate the theoretical amount of land area occupied by the non-decomposed MSW).

Note that the terms landfilled and added to landfills will be used interchangeably.

Historical landfills and future projections¶

The amount of each MSW type landfilled in previous years is available (Fig. 1), albeit with gaps between years reporting data. However, for the model to work, it needs a projection for future years of the amount of each MSW type landfilled. In this work, we simulate the model with the assumption of constant landfill additions. Before then, we must provide a justification for this decision.

First, it is worth noting that while MSW landfill additions increased rapidly between 1960 and 1990, they roughly plateaued after the 2000s (Fig. 1). This trend can partly be explained by the rise in the rate of recycling and composting, which increased from 10% of MSW generated in 1985 to 34% of MSW generated in 2010. However, the rate of recycling and composting has remained flat since 2010 [1]. A full explanation of the plateau in annual MSW landfill additions since 1990 is made clear by trends in annual MSW generation per capita, which has remained roughly flat at 0.75 metric tons per person per year (Fig 2.). Therefore, flattening of MSW landfill additions over the last two decades can be attributed to the flattening of MSW generation, whether the waste was landfilled, recycled, combusted, or composted.

Such a stagnation might be attributed to the Jevons paradox, which says that increases in efficiency are counterbalanced by increases in consumption such that the total production level remains roughly flat [3]. It is not unreasonable to assume that such a trend would continue into future years. MSW generation per capita cannot increase indefinitely and is likely to eventually plateau as consumers face diminishing marginal utility in generating MSW. Whether a plateau in MSW generation per capita has been reached at this point is debatable, though it is clearly unreasonable to project landfill additions as continuing upwards indefinitely. Whether it is now or at some point in the future, a plateau can be expected.

Figure 2. The amount of MSW generated per person per year in the United States for each of the available years from 1960 to 2017. [1]

Figure 3. The amount of each MSW type landfilled in the United States in 2017. [2]

Decomposition as exponential decay¶

The precise decomposition functions over time for each of the MSW types is either not generally known or has a high degree of uncertainty. There is evidence that the decomposition of plastics follows a function similar to an exponential decay with a steep negative slope early on that gradually flattens while still remaining negative [7]. However, it is not generally known what the decomposition functions are for other MSW types. Exponential decay, which results from the decay rate being directly proportional to the amount of type, seems to be the most elemental function of decomposition without being over simplistic.

Estimating rate constants from decomposition times¶

If exponential decay is the best estimate under uncertainty for the structure of the decomposition functions for each of the MSW types, it remains to be known what the decay constants are for the different MSW types. These can be estimated using the decomposition times provided by a variety of sources. Estimates for the decomposition times of food, rubber and leather, textiles, aluminum, and glass can be obtained from the Mote Marine Lab [4]. An estimate for the decomposition time of paper in landfills is provided by Ximenes [5]. An estimate for the decomposition time of wood products in landfills can be calculated by the measured loss of wood products original carbon content in landfills provided by Ximenes et al. [6]. Commonly quoted decomposition times and estimates based on similar types can be used for yard trimmings, steel, and plastic.

Figure 4. The reported decomposition time of each MSW type. [4, 5, 6]

Because exponential decay functions never reach zero, there must be a declared 'percent remaining' at the point of the decomposition time. Here, we use the relatively conservative number of 5%. That is, at the decomposition time for the MSW type, 5% is still remaining to decompose. This parameter is given by $R$:


$$R = 0.05$$

The decomposition functions are likely the greatest source of uncertainty in any model of non-decomposed MSW type in landfills over time.

Converting mass to volume and land area¶

Estimating densities¶

The densities of certain baled or compressed MSW types can be obtained from the volume to weight conversions provided by the EPA [8]. Estimates of the density of wood in landfills is provided by Ximenes et al. [6]. For other MSW types such as rubber and leather, and glass, densities can be obtained from the standard widely available measurements. In some cases, the volume to weight conversions provided by the EPA are only available for a limited number of instances of a MSW type. For example, baled aluminum cans has the only provided density by the EPA for aluminum. In those cases, an average can be made between the standard widely available density of that MSW type and the EPA provided density. This is required for steel and aluminum, which have limited measurements provided by the EPA.

Figure 4. The reported density of each MSW type. [6, 8]

We can check the reliability of the reported densities by taking their weighted average, where the weights are the 2017 landfill additions shown in Fig. 3. This weighted average can then be compared with the overall density of MSW provided by the EPA [1].

The weighted mean of the literature-reported MSW type densities was 0.90 meter tons per cubic meter whereas the overall density provided by the EPA was 1.07 metric tons per cubic meter. The weighted mean of 0.90 then shows moderate agreement and is a less optimistic estimate, as lower density implies greater volume and land area.

Estimating representative depth¶

The median landfill depth in the United States can be obtained from the EPAs Landfill Methane Outreach Program (LMOP) database (n = 2,549 landfills). While the LMOP database does not contain information on every landfill in the United States, it is the most comprehensive dataset available. The current median depth of 24.1 meters is used. It may be worth noting that the 25th and 75th percentiles are 15.2 and 33.4 meters for the current landfill depth, and 16.8 and 39.6 meters for the design landfill depth [9].

Mathematical formulation¶

Introduction to terms¶

  • There are $m$ MSW types, e.g., glass, plastic, etc.
  • Each waste type is denoted by $i \in \{1, 2, \dots , m\}$ and has a decomposition rate constant $k_i$. It will be shown how these are estimated from data.
  • MSW is landfilled during years $t_j$, where $j \in \{0, 1, \dots , n\}$ and $t_j = t_0 + j$. For instance, $t_0$ might be $1960$.
  • We will generally consider the amount of MSW during year $t_n$, which means $t_n \leq t < t_{n+1}$.

The landfill addition from a given year¶

Let $A_i(t_j)$ be the landfill addition in year $t_j$ of waste type $i$, measured in mass (metric tons).

For instance, $A_i(t_j)$ might be the 27.8 million metric tons of food landfilled in 2017. Note that $A_i(t_j)$ is interpolated from the EPA data and projected for future years.

Then, let $W_i(t, t_j)$ be the amount of non-decomposed MSW of type $i$ at time $t$, remaining from the landfill addition $A_i(t_j)$ during year $t_j$.

Our exponential model of decomposition says the following:


$$\large W_i(t, t_j) = A_i(t_j) \, e^{-k_i(t - t_j - 1)}$$


For $t \geq t_j + 1$, and during year $t_j$, we have:


$$\large W_i(t, t_j) = A_i(t_j) (t - t_j)$$


Notice that we make the minor approximation that there is no decomposition during year $t_j$ as the MSW is added that year. Decomposition begins at the beginning of the next year - once all of $A_i(t_j)$ has been added.

Estimating rate constants from decomposition times¶

We discussed earlier how we calculate the rate constants for MSW types from their reported decomposition times. This is accomplished by setting the 'percent remaining' at the decomposition time to a constant $R$, which was chosen to be 5%. This means that at time $t = T_i$, where $T_i$ is the reported decomposition time of MSW type $i$, we have:


$$\large \frac{W_i(T_i, t_j)}{A_i(t_j)} = R = 0.05$$


Then, we can calculate $k_i$, where 'log' is the natural logarithm:


$$\large k_i = \frac{\mathrm{log}(R)}{T_i}$$


The total amount of non-decomposed MSW of a certain type¶

Let $W_i(t)$ be the total amount of non-decomposed waste of type $i$ at time $t$. We assume $t$ is during year $t_n$, such that $t_n \leq t < t_{n+1}$. From our earlier equations we get the following equation:


$$\large W_i(t) = A_i(t_n) (t - t_n) + \sum_{j=0}^{n-1} W_i(t, t_j)$$


Note that the summation does not occur if $n = 0$, and that all the $W_i(t, t_j)$ in the summation are in their exponential form. Then, because the summation is $W_i(t_n)$ and the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives, we can obtain the rate of change in the amount of non-decomposed MSW of type $i$ at time $t$.


$$\large \frac{d W_i(t)}{dt} = A_i(t_n) -k_i W_i(t_n)$$


Note that this equation does not hold at exactly $t = t_n$, which is a relatively unimportant hole in the function.

It is important to notice that $-k_i W_i(t_n)$ is the amount that gets decomposed and $A_i(t_n)$ is the amount that gets added. Steady state is reached when these two terms are equal. Then, the total amount of non-decomposed MSW of type $i$ remains steady over time.

Aluminum example¶

As an example, here we can see the exponential decay of the MSW type aluminum from the landfill addition of a single year. We start with the 2.4 million metric tons added that year, which decays over time with the equation for $W_i(t, t_j)$.

We will show how this can also be approximated by an exponential function.

The total amount of non-decomposed MSW of all types¶

Let $W(t)$ be the total amount of non-decomposed waste at time $t$. Similarly, let $A(t_j)$ be the total amount of MSW landfilled in year $t_j$. We then have the following simple equations:


$$\large W(t) = \sum_{i=1}^m W_i(t)$$


$$\large A(t_j) = \sum_{i=1}^m A_i(t_j)$$

Then, for the rate of change, we get:


$$\large \frac{d W(t)}{dt} = A(t_n) -\sum_{i=1}^m k_i W_i(t_n)$$

Because $A(t_j)$ can have any arbitrary function over time, such as observed data points, the equations for $W_i(t)$ and $W(t)$ are computed numerically.

Converting between mass, volume, and depth¶

Let $\rho_i$ be the density of MSW type $i$, which is a literature measurement, and let $d$ be the observed median depth of US landfills. Then, we have:


$$\large V_i = \frac{W_i}{\rho_i}$$


$$\large L_i = \frac{V_i}{d}$$

Where $V_i$ and $L_i$ are the volume and land-area, respectively, taken up by non-decomposed MSW waste type $i$. As before, the $V_i$ and $L_i$ can sum to the totals $V$ and $L$, respectively. Also, $V_i$ and $L_i$ can have any function of time that $W_i$ has, e.g. $V_i(t, t_j)$ or $L_i(t)$.

Constant additions (plateau)¶

Suppose that for years $t_j \geq t_c$ landfill additions are constant for MSW type $i$, that is, all $A_i(t_j) = A_i$. Note that we can even allow $t_c$ to be zero, then landfill additions are constant for all years. However, we will use this to describe a projected future of constant landfill additions.

We will introduce a few new terms to better handle this paradigm. Let ${}_{c}W_i(t)$ be the amount of non-decomposed MSW from additions in years $t_c$ through $t_{n-1}$, and let ${}_{b}W_i(t)$ be the amount of non-decomposed MSW from additions in the years before $t_c$ (years $t_0$ through $t_{c-1}$). Then we have the following equations:


$$\large W_i(t) = A_i(t - t_n) + {}_{b}W_i(t) + {}_{c}W_i(t_n)$$


$$\large{}_{b}W_i(t_n) = \sum_{j=0}^{c-1} A_i(t_j) \, e^{-k_i(t - t_j - 1)}$$


$$\large {}_{c}W_i(t_n) = A_i \sum_{j=c}^{n-1} e^{-k_i(t_n - t_j - 1)}$$

We can apply the Riemann sum approximation to ${}_{c}W_i(t_n)$ to get the following:


$$\large {}_{c}W_i(t_n) \approx A_i \int_{t_c}^{t_{n-1}} e^{-k_i(t_n - t_j - 1)} dt_j$$

This expression is actually more accurate, because it drops our earlier approximation that landfill additions only begin decomposing once the year ends. We can solve this integral, knowing that $t_{n-1} = t_n - 1$.


$$\large {}_{c}W_i(t_n) \approx \frac{A_i}{k_i} [ 1 - e^{-k_i(t_n - t_c - 1)}]$$

This provides us with an excellent approximation for constant additions. The fact that we get a curve of this shape is very apparent in the aluminum example. Importantly, this equation says that the non-decomposed MSW from the years of constant additions asymptotically approaches $\frac{A_i}{k_i}$.

Steady state under plateau¶

We would like to show that $W_i(t)$ approaches a steady state far into the future, as $t \rightarrow \infty$. It's very clear that ${}_{b}W_i(t)$ approaches zero for large $t$ because each of the terms in its finite summation approaches zero. Then, for large $t$, we get:


$$\large W_i(t) \rightarrow A_i(t - t_n) + {}_{c}W_i(t_n)$$

Steady state means the rate of change is zero, so we take the derivative and set it equal to zero. For taking the derivative of ${}_{c}W_i(t_n)$, we refer to its summation form. Again, the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives, the constant $k_i$ comes out of the expression so that we get, for large $t$:


$$\large \frac{d W_i(t)}{dt} \approx A_i - k_i \, {}_{c}W_i(t_n) = 0 $$

Thus, in order to reach steady state, we need the following for $t \rightarrow \infty$:


$$\large {}_{c}W_i(t_n) \rightarrow \frac{A_i}{k_i}$$

Yet this is exactly what our Riemann sum approximation says will happen! Therefore, we have shown that constant additions, the steady state $\frac{A_i}{k_i}$ is asymptotically approached, regardless of the previous years' additions.

We project that the US continues its 2017 additions of each MSW type.

Paper tends to level off below its peak. Plastic, wood, and glass appear to drive the long-term upward trajectory.

Eventual stabilization¶

If the US continues its 2017 additions of each MSW type, eventually the rate of landfill addition equals the rate of landfill decomposition. In other words, steady state is reached.

Steady state is reached in the year ~2,700,000, with about 2 trillion metric tons of mostly glass. It becomes clear that the lengthy decomposition-time of glass makes it unsustainable to landfill.

If the US were to stop landfilling glass in the year 2200¶

Glass should be recycled or combusted for energy use. After many centuries, the un-decomposed remains of glass to take up large amounts of space, far more than plastic.

Let's suppose the US bans the landfilling of glass in the year 2200.

The result is a big improvement. We can reach steady state in the year 4,300 at around 14 billion metric tons.

It's even clear when the ban went into effect: observe the sharp bend in the year 2200.

Non-decomposed MSW stabilizes at about 1,400 square kilometers, roughly the size of Rhode Island (3,100 sq km).

For some perspective, consider that 515,000 square kilometers of the US is occupied by cropland for livestock [10], roughly the size of California (425,000 square kilometers).

Discussion¶

Glass has a relatively small annual addition amount of 6.23 million metric tons, though it takes roughly 1,000,000 years to decompose. Although plastic has four times the rate of annual additions to landfills, glass has a factor of one-thousand greater decomposition time.

Organic MSW types such as food, yard trimmings, and paper have substantial annual contributions to landfills, but have very low decomposition times. Therefore, these types of MSW do not contribute much to the overall amount of non-decomposed MSW in future landfills.
